title: Documentation
text: Policy measures provided Oxford Covid-19 Government Response Tracker. documentation: “Policies often vary region within countries. Tracker codes stringent government policy place country/territory, represented highest ordinal value. Sometimes stringent policy country/territory apply small part population. stringent policy present limited geographic area, Tracker uses binary flag variable denote limited scope. indicators flag whether ”targeted" specific geographical region (flag=0) whether “general” policy applied across whole country/territory (flag=1)." COVID-19 Data Hub uses flags indicators follows: General policies (flag=1) encoded positive value. Targeted policies (flag=0) encoded negative value. Missing flags treated flag=0 (targeted policy) represent fact policy may vary within country. policies country used also sub-national areas (levels 2 3), unless sub-national policies directly available. data sub-national policies available (level 2), policies level 3 inherited policies level 2. short: positive integers identify policies applied entire administrative area. Negative integers used identify policies represent best guess policy force, may represent real status given area. negative sign used solely distinguish two cases, treated real negative value. Oxford Covid-19 Government Response Tracker calculates several indices give overall impression government activity, described . COVID-19 Data Hub propagates index value upper level areas lower level areas described individual policy measures. index provided directly given area inherited upper level area, place minus sign front value index. negative sign used solely distinguish two cases, treated real negative value.

title: Style Guide
text: COVID-19 Data Hub developed around 2 concepts: data sources countries extract data one country, different data sources may required. reason, important keep two concepts distinct. code R folder organized two main types files: files representing data source (prefix ds_) files representing country (prefix iso_) R comments prefixed #' used generate documentation roxygen2. comments prefixed # used generate documentation. package set support usage Rmarkdown syntax docstring. documentation block (#') starts uppercase ends blank line. non-documentation comment (#) include blank line starts lowercase.
code: #' This is a documentation block #' code here...  # this is a comment not used in the documentation code here...

title: Style Guide
text: ds_ files named according domain website data provided (e.g. example.com). subdomain included (e.g., sub.example.com becomes example.com). instance, data pulled https://coronavirus.data.gov.uk/details/developers-guide file named ds_gov.uk.R. GitHub repositories, use github.username.repository (lowercase). Hyphens dashes dropped. instance https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19 becomes ds_github.cssegisanddata.covid19.R open data sharing portals, https://www.arcgis.com, use domain portal suffix corresponding Alpha-2 ISO 3166-1 code country providing data. example, Swedish Public Health Agency proving data https://www.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=b5e7488e117749c19881cce45db13f7e becomes ds_arcgis.se.R (SE 2 letter ISO code Sweden).

title: Style Guide
text: ds_ file implements R function responsible download data provider format data.frame column date (mandatory) columns (optional). order irrelevant columns need provided. Additional columns may included. function takes argument level input. may implement additional arguments well. function starts condition make clear level supported. function name corresponding ds_ file (without prefix ds_ without suffix .R).
code: github.eguidotti.covid19br <- function(level){   if(level!=3) return(NULL)        # code here...      }

title: Style Guide
text: documentation starts name data provider. name data provider : official name organizations (preferably English) name individuals (e.g., personal GitHub repositories) description “Data source :” followed name country data provided. comma-separated list countries multiple countries supported. Use “Worldwide” worldwide data source. rest documentation block generated function ds_docstring package (copy-paste output file).

text: iso_ files named according Alpha-3 ISO 3166-1 code country. instance, file United States named iso_USA.R (USA 3 letter ISO code United States).

title: Style Guide
code: #' Brazil  #' #' @source \url{`r repo("BRA")`} #'  BRA <- function(level){   x <- NULL      #' @concept Level 1   #' @section Data Sources:   #'    #' ## Level 1   #' `r docstring("BRA", 1)`   #'    if(level==1){          #' - \href{`r repo("github.wcota.covid19br")`}{Wesley Cota}:     #' confirmed cases,     #' deaths,     #' recovered,     #' tests,     #' total vaccine doses administered.     #'     x <- github.wcota.covid19br(level = level)       }      #' @concept Level 2   #' @section Data Sources:   #'    #' ## Level 2   #' `r docstring("BRA", 2)`   #'    if(level==2){          #' - \href{`r repo("github.wcota.covid19br")`}{Wesley Cota}:     #' confirmed cases,     #' deaths,     #' recovered,     #' tests,     #' total vaccine doses administered.     #'     x <- github.wcota.covid19br(level = level)     x$id <- id(x$state, iso = "BRA", ds = "github.wcota.covid19br", level = level)        }      #' @concept Level 3   #' @section Data Sources:   #'    #' ## Level 3   #' `r docstring("BRA", 3)`   #'    if(level==3){        #' - \href{`r repo("github.wcota.covid19br")`}{Wesley Cota}:     #' confirmed cases,     #' deaths.     #'     x <- github.wcota.covid19br(level = level)     x$id <- id(x$code, iso = "BRA", ds = "github.wcota.covid19br", level = level)          #' - \href{`r repo("github.eguidotti.covid19br")`}{Emanuele Guidotti}:     #' total vaccine doses administered,     #' people with at least one vaccine dose,     #' people fully vaccinated.     #'     v <- github.eguidotti.covid19br(level = level)     v$id <- id(v$ibge, iso = "BRA", ds = "github.eguidotti.covid19br", level = level)          # merge     x <- dplyr::left_join(x, v, by = c("id", "date"))        }      return(x) }
